# SECTION 2 — HTTP Versioning

## What is HTTP?

**HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol)** is the **communication protocol** used to transfer data between a client (browser) and a server on the internet.

**Simple words:** When you type a URL in your browser, your browser sends an HTTP request to the server. The server replies with an HTTP response containing the webpage. HTTP defines the rules for this communication.

## HTTP Versions — Evolution

### HTTP/1.0 (1996)
- Each request opens a **new connection** and closes it after the response
- Very slow — every image, CSS, JS file needs a new connection
- **One request per connection**

```
Browser ──connect──► Server ──response──► disconnect
Browser ──connect──► Server ──response──► disconnect  (for each file!)
```

### HTTP/1.1 (1997) — Most widely used for years
- Introduced **persistent connections** — connection stays open for multiple requests
- Introduced **pipelining** — multiple requests can be sent without waiting for each response
- But still processes responses **in order** — if one request is slow, everything waits (Head-of-Line blocking)

```
Browser ──connect──► Server
         request 1 ──────────► response 1
         request 2 ──────────► response 2   (same connection)
         request 3 ──────────► response 3
```

### HTTP/2 (2015) — Big improvement
- **Multiplexing** — multiple requests and responses at the same time over one connection, no waiting
- **Header compression** — reduces data sent by compressing request headers
- **Server push** — server can send files the browser will need before it even asks
- **Binary protocol** — data sent as binary instead of text, faster to parse
- No Head-of-Line blocking at HTTP level

```
Browser ──connect──► Server
         request 1 ─────────► response 1 ┐
         request 2 ─────────► response 2 │ All at same time!
         request 3 ─────────► response 3 ┘
```

### HTTP/3 (2022) — Latest
- Uses **QUIC protocol** instead of TCP — built on UDP
- **Faster connection setup** — 0-RTT (zero round trip time) for returning users
- **Better performance on mobile** — handles network switching (WiFi to 4G) without dropping connections
- Fixes Head-of-Line blocking completely even at transport level
- Used by Google, Facebook, Cloudflare

## HTTP Versions — Quick Comparison

| Feature | HTTP/1.0 | HTTP/1.1 | HTTP/2 | HTTP/3 |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Year | 1996 | 1997 | 2015 | 2022 |
| Connection | New per request | Persistent | Persistent | QUIC (UDP) |
| Multiplexing | No | No | Yes | Yes |
| Header compression | No | No | Yes | Yes |
| Server Push | No | No | Yes | Yes |
| Protocol | Text | Text | Binary | Binary |
| Speed | Slowest | Slow | Fast | Fastest |

## Simple Memory Tip
- HTTP/1.0 → One connection, one request, done
- HTTP/1.1 → Same connection, multiple requests, one by one
- HTTP/2 → Same connection, all requests at once
- HTTP/3 → Faster connection, all requests at once, works better on mobile

