# SECTION 3 — Array vs Linked List (Deep Comparison)

## Memory Layout

**Array — Contiguous Memory:**
```
Address: 100  104  108  112  116
Value:   [10] [20] [30] [40] [50]
```
All elements side by side. Address of element = base + (index × size)

**Linked List — Scattered Memory:**
```
Address: 100       250       430       610
Node:   [10|250] [20|430] [30|610] [40|null]
```
Each node at a different location, connected by pointers.

## Why Array Access is O(1) but Linked List is O(n)

**Array:**
- To get element at index 3 → address = 100 + (3 × 4) = 112
- Jump directly to address 112 — instant!

**Linked List:**
- To get node at position 3 → start at head (100) → go to 250 → go to 430 → go to 610
- Must hop through every node one by one — takes O(n) time

## Insert at Beginning

**Array — O(n):**
```
Insert 5 at beginning of [10, 20, 30, 40]
Step 1: Shift 40 → position 4
Step 2: Shift 30 → position 3
Step 3: Shift 20 → position 2
Step 4: Shift 10 → position 1
Step 5: Place 5 at position 0
Result: [5, 10, 20, 30, 40]
— Every element must shift!
```

**Linked List — O(1):**
```
Insert 5 at beginning of 10→20→30→40
Step 1: Create new node [5]
Step 2: Set new node's next → head (10)
Step 3: Update head → new node (5)
Result: 5→10→20→30→40
— Only pointers change, no shifting!
```

## Full Comparison Table

| Feature | Array | Linked List |
|---|---|---|
| Memory storage | Contiguous | Scattered |
| Size | Fixed (static) | Dynamic |
| Access by index | O(1) — direct | O(n) — traverse |
| Search | O(n) linear / O(log n) binary | O(n) only |
| Insert at beginning | O(n) — shift | O(1) — pointer |
| Insert at end | O(1) | O(n) singly / O(1) doubly |
| Insert at middle | O(n) — shift | O(n) — find + O(1) insert |
| Delete at beginning | O(n) — shift | O(1) — pointer |
| Delete at end | O(1) | O(n) singly / O(1) doubly |
| Memory per element | Low (no pointer) | High (data + pointer) |
| Cache performance | Excellent | Poor |
| Binary search | Possible | Not possible |
| Use when | Fast access needed | Frequent insert/delete |

