# SECTION 9 — Recursion Clarity

## How Recursion Actually Flows — Visual

```
factorial(4)
│
├── returns 4 × factorial(3)
│              │
│              ├── returns 3 × factorial(2)
│              │              │
│              │              ├── returns 2 × factorial(1)
│              │              │              │
│              │              │              └── returns 1  ← BASE CASE
│              │              │
│              │              └── 2 × 1 = 2
│              │
│              └── 3 × 2 = 6
│
└── 4 × 6 = 24  ← FINAL ANSWER
```

## The Golden Rules of Recursion

1. **Always have a base case** — without it, infinite recursion → Stack Overflow
2. **Each call must move towards base case** — input must get smaller each time
3. **Trust the recursion** — assume the recursive call returns the correct answer

## Common Mistake — Missing Base Case
```js
// WRONG — no base case, infinite recursion!
function sum(n) {
  return n + sum(n - 1);  // never stops!
}

// CORRECT — with base case
function sum(n) {
  if (n === 0) return 0;  // base case
  return n + sum(n - 1);  // recursive case
}
```

