# SECTION 10 — Iteration vs Recursion (Deep Comparison)

## Same Problem — Two Approaches

**Problem: Find factorial of n**

### Iterative Approach
```js
function factorialIterative(n) {
  let result = 1;
  for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
    result = result * i;
  }
  return result;
}
console.log(factorialIterative(5)); // 120
```

**How it runs:**
```
i=1: result = 1 × 1 = 1
i=2: result = 1 × 2 = 2
i=3: result = 2 × 3 = 6
i=4: result = 6 × 4 = 24
i=5: result = 24 × 5 = 120
Done!
```

### Recursive Approach
```js
function factorialRecursive(n) {
  if (n === 0) return 1;
  return n * factorialRecursive(n - 1);
}
console.log(factorialRecursive(5)); // 120
```

**How it runs:**
```
factorialRecursive(5)
= 5 × factorialRecursive(4)
= 5 × 4 × factorialRecursive(3)
= 5 × 4 × 3 × factorialRecursive(2)
= 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × factorialRecursive(1)
= 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 × factorialRecursive(0)
= 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 × 1
= 120
```

## Iteration vs Recursion — Full Comparison

| Feature | Iteration | Recursion |
|---|---|---|
| Uses | Loop (for/while) | Function calling itself |
| Memory | O(1) — no call stack | O(n) — call stack grows |
| Speed | Faster | Slightly slower (function call overhead) |
| Risk | Infinite loop | Stack Overflow |
| Stop condition | Loop condition false | Base case reached |
| Readability | Better for simple tasks | Better for complex/nested problems |
| Code length | Sometimes longer | Usually shorter |
| Best for | Simple repetition | Trees, graphs, divide & conquer |

## When to Choose Which

**Use Iteration when:**
- Simple counting or looping
- Memory efficiency is important
- Performance is critical
- No natural recursive structure

**Use Recursion when:**
- Problem has a naturally self-similar structure
- Working with Trees, Graphs
- Implementing Merge Sort, Quick Sort
- Writing cleaner and more readable code for complex problems

