## Viva Q&A

**Q1. What is a CDN and why is it used?**
A CDN or Content Delivery Network is a network of servers distributed across the world that delivers content to users from the server closest to them. It is used to make websites load faster, reduce the load on the origin server, improve availability, and provide DDoS protection.

**Q2. What is the main difference between HTTP/1.1 and HTTP/2?**
HTTP/1.1 uses persistent connections but processes requests one by one, causing Head-of-Line blocking where a slow request delays all others. HTTP/2 introduces multiplexing which allows multiple requests and responses to travel simultaneously over a single connection, eliminating this bottleneck and making it significantly faster.

**Q3. What is HTTP/3 and what makes it different?**
HTTP/3 is the latest version of HTTP that uses QUIC protocol built on UDP instead of TCP. It offers faster connection setup with zero round trip time for returning users, handles network switching without dropping connections, and eliminates Head-of-Line blocking completely at the transport level.

**Q4. Why is array access O(1) but linked list access O(n)?**
Array elements are stored in contiguous memory. The address of any element is calculated directly using base address plus index multiplied by element size, allowing instant access. In a linked list, elements are scattered in memory and connected by pointers. To reach any element, we must traverse from the head and follow pointers one by one, which takes O(n) time.

**Q5. Why is insertion at the beginning O(1) in linked list but O(n) in array?**
In a linked list, we only need to create a new node, point it to the current head, and update head to the new node. No elements are moved. In an array, all existing elements must shift one position to the right to make space for the new element, which takes O(n) time.

**Q6. What is the difference between Stack and Heap memory?**
Stack memory is small, fast, and automatically managed by the OS. It stores local variables and function call frames in LIFO order and is freed automatically when a function returns. Heap memory is large, flexible, and managed by the garbage collector or manually by the programmer. It stores dynamically created objects and arrays and remains until explicitly freed or garbage collected.

**Q7. What are the three types of memory allocation?**
Static memory allocation happens at compile time with fixed size and is stored in the Stack. Dynamic memory allocation happens at runtime with flexible size and is stored in the Heap. Automatic memory allocation is handled by the language runtime through garbage collection, as in JavaScript, Java, and Python.

**Q8. What is the difference between Iteration and Recursion?**
Iteration uses loops like for or while and solves problems with O(1) space. Recursion uses a function that calls itself and uses O(n) space due to the call stack. Iteration is faster and more memory efficient. Recursion is more readable and natural for problems with self-similar structure like tree traversal and divide and conquer algorithms.

**Q9. Explain sum of array using recursion.**
We define the sum of an array as the first element plus the sum of the remaining elements. The base case is when the index reaches the length of the array, returning 0. The recursive case returns arr[index] plus sumArray(arr, index + 1). This visits each element once giving O(n) time complexity and O(n) space for the call stack.

**Q10. Why does recursive Binary Search have O(log n) space complexity?**
Because each recursive call creates a new stack frame in the call stack. Binary Search halves the array at each step, so it makes at most log n recursive calls. Each call adds one frame to the stack, resulting in O(log n) space. The iterative version avoids this by using a loop instead, giving O(1) space.

**Q11. What are the three asymptotic notations and what do they represent?**
Big O represents the worst case or upper bound — the maximum time an algorithm can take. Big Omega represents the best case or lower bound — the minimum time possible. Big Theta represents the tight bound — used when the algorithm always grows at the same rate regardless of input, meaning best and worst case have the same growth.

**Q12. What is the difference between O(n) and O(n²) with a practical example?**
O(n) means time grows linearly. For 1000 elements it takes 1000 steps. O(n²) means time grows as the square of input. For 1000 elements it takes 1,000,000 steps. O(n) is a single loop and O(n²) is a nested loop. Bubble sort with O(n²) is 1000 times slower than linear search with O(n) for 1000 elements.

